subsection.p:
Comparing these observations with the form for a linear model, we see that
\blert{y} \amp =(\blert{\text{starting value}} ) +(\blert{\text{rate}})\cdot x \blert{y} \amp = \hphantom{startin}\blert{b} \hphantom{value}  + ~~ \blert{mx} 
Usually we write the terms in the opposite order, like this: y = mx + b. We call this last equation the slope-intercept form  for a line.

